TY  - JOUR
T1  - Merton H. Miller: His Contribution to Financial Economics
AU  - Grundy, Bruce D.
Y1  - 2001/08/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00364
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1183
EP  - 1206
VL  - 56
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00364
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Merton Miller's status as a father of finance reflects the academic depth, breadth, and rigor of his writings and two important facets of his character. Merton was a man of great warmth and humor. He communicated his often challenging views via memorable phrases and anecdotes that have become part of the everyday language of the profession. Merton was also a man of great dedication. The whole profession has benefited from his devotion to his doctoral students, to his colleagues, and to his coauthors. This essay demonstrates how Merton's admiration for markets provided the foundation for all his research.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Equity Premium and Structural Breaks
AU  - Pástor, Ľluboš
AU  - Stambaugh, Robert F.
Y1  - 2001/08/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00365
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1207
EP  - 1239
VL  - 56
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00365
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - A long return history is useful in estimating the current equity premium even if the historical distribution has experienced structural breaks. The long series helps not only if the timing of breaks is uncertain but also if one believes that large shifts in the premium are unlikely or that the premium is associated, in part, with volatility. Our framework incorporates these features along with a belief that prices are likely to move opposite to contemporaneous shifts in the premium. The estimated premium since 1834 fluctuates between 4 and 6 percent and exhibits its sharpest drop in the last decade.
ER  - 

